<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/7A0397DD-E0C6-4EA3-8031-B841D2503C4D"><gtr:id>7A0397DD-E0C6-4EA3-8031-B841D2503C4D</gtr:id><gtr:name>Royal Holloway, University of London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Geography</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Egham Hill</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Egham</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Surrey</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>TW20 0EX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/7A0397DD-E0C6-4EA3-8031-B841D2503C4D"><gtr:id>7A0397DD-E0C6-4EA3-8031-B841D2503C4D</gtr:id><gtr:name>Royal Holloway, University of London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Egham Hill</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Egham</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Surrey</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>TW20 0EX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/6E19DA18-08CE-4336-BB26-FD90AC5273D2"><gtr:id>6E19DA18-08CE-4336-BB26-FD90AC5273D2</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Fernando</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Garcia</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>RESEARCHER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=PTA-026-27-0968"><gtr:id>8EEEFB15-9094-4C6E-9F39-20C4068F9448</gtr:id><gtr:title>Cafe Culture: Creating Convivial Cities</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>PTA-026-27-0968</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project is concerned with the ways in which cosmopolitan cities are shaped around the needs of its people to come together, or con-vive. Whether as members of social groups (eg sexual, ethnic or neighbourhood communities) or as solitary consumer-citizens, urban individuals often feel the need to seek out spaces in the city in which the presence of others is proximate. Such conviviality, or togetherness and how cities are made liveable, emancipatory and somehow real, is the subject of this research project. Spaces of conviviality are crucial either because they enact moments of encounter in cities of diversity and therefore proliferate a cultural geography of toleration, if not emancipation, or because they provide everyday opportunities for individuals to enjoy their everyday lives (in their city) and fulfil certain urges to be alone, in contemplation, yet in the presence of nearby others. Specifically, attention is focused on the urban-spatial practices which have traditionally fallen under the rubric of ?public space? (eg squares, streets, parks) but&amp;nbsp;which here will be extended into more appropriate notions of ?public domain? or ?public culture?, thus taking in alternative spaces of sociability and hospitality such as caf&amp;eacute;s.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The project will look to, and speak to, urban interventionists such as planners, designers, architects, entrepreneurs and citizen-consumers of various cities (mainly London, Lisbon, and Madrid) in order to gauge how cities of difference and diversity are best shaped around the potential for everyday encounters between home and work, through vibrant caf&amp;eacute; cultures (of which the Continental form is often celebrated; hence the UK-Iberian comparisons). &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The project builds on PhD research (?Caf&amp;eacute; Culture: Cosmopolitanism, Public Culture and Contemplation in Madrid?, 2005), which analysed Madrid?s vibrant caf&amp;eacute; scenes and their relationships with urban lives and lifestyles, cultures and everyday economies of hospitality in the central barrio of Chueca (an urban quarter famed for recent regeneration into a vibrant queer space in which various social groups con-vive).&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The research findings will be&amp;nbsp;disseminated and communicated in a number of ways, including: organising and hosting a number of workshops; preparing papers for publication in international peer-reviewed journals, chapters in edited collections, and articles for urban practitioner, interventionist and popular publications; attending national and international conferences; and continued teaching on a number of courses on cultural and urban geography/studies.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2006-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>25062</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">PTA-026-27-0968</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>B57EEFB7-602E-4F5D-92E4-A0C265266249</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Demography &amp; human geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>3A4CB57C-9B22-41A2-AB15-127503299365</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Human Geography</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>